---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { autoUrl, forgeUrl, githubOrgUrl, marketUrl, profileUrl } from '../data/products';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="About AgentKitProject, the open ecosystem for portable Agent Kits."
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
      <h1>Agent Kits are the next step after prompts and skills.</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        AgentKitProject builds the open tools for that step: a portable package format for AI
        instructions, skills, prompts, policies, and context, plus the identity, distribution, and
        automation layers a package format needs to actually get used. Local-first, open ecosystem,
        no vendor lock-in, self-hostable.
      </p>
      <div class="button-row">
        <a class="button" href={githubOrgUrl}>View GitHub organization</a>
        <a class="button secondary" href={forgeUrl}>Start with Forge</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section tight">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">The next evolution of skills</p>
      <h2>A prompt in a chat window doesn't travel. A kit does.</h2>
      <p>
        Most AI work today lives as one-off prompts or ad-hoc "skills": useful in the moment, but
        stuck in a single chat, a single tool, a single person's head. They're hard to version,
        hard to review, hard to hand to a teammate, and impossible to run on their own.
      </p>
      <p>
        An <strong>Agent Kit</strong> is a portable <code>.agentkit.zip</code> package —
        instructions, guardrails, examples, and expected outputs bundled into one artifact. Because
        it's a real artifact and not a paste buffer, it can be inspected, versioned, reviewed,
        shared, sold, and run anywhere — in a browser, from a CLI, or on a schedule. That's the
        shift: a skill stops being a snippet locked in one conversation and becomes a durable,
        portable, runnable asset.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section tight">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">One ecosystem, one lifecycle</p>
      <h2>Identify, build, share, and automate — as one flow.</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        Each product below is independently usable. Together, they cover the full lifecycle of a
        kit from first draft to unattended execution.
      </p>
      <div class="grid two">
        <article class="content-panel">
          <h3>AgentKitProfile — identify</h3>
          <p>
            Shared identity and organizations across the ecosystem. One account, one profile,
            one place to manage team membership and roles across Forge, Market, and Auto.
          </p>
          <p><a href={profileUrl}>Open AgentKitProfile account</a></p>
        </article>
        <article class="content-panel">
          <h3>AgentKitForge — build</h3>
          <p>
            Create, edit, validate, package, export, import, and run Agent Kits, in the browser
            or from the <code>agentkitforge</code> CLI. Local-first: no account or server required
            to build and run a kit on your own machine.
          </p>
          <p><a href={forgeUrl}>Open AgentKitForge</a></p>
        </article>
        <article class="content-panel">
          <h3>AgentKitMarket — share</h3>
          <p>
            Publish, discover, review, and distribute kits through a validated catalog — with
            organizations, private catalogs, and paid kits for sellers who want to charge for
            their work.
          </p>
          <p><a href={marketUrl}>Browse AgentKitMarket</a></p>
        </article>
        <article class="content-panel">
          <h3>AgentKitAuto — automate</h3>
          <p>
            Run trusted kits automatically — on demand, on a schedule, or from events and webhook
            triggers — instead of kicking them off by hand every time.
          </p>
          <p><a href={autoUrl}>Open AgentKitAuto</a></p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section tight">
    <div class="container grid two">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Open foundation</p>
        <h2>The core and CLI are open source, and the whole stack is self-hostable.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="content-panel">
        <p>
          Underneath Forge, Market, and Auto is an open-source core engine and CLI
          (<code>@agentkitforge/core</code>, <code>agentkitforge</code>) that owns the kit spec,
          validation, and packaging — the same engine every product builds on. Nothing about the
          format or the local workflow depends on a hosted service, and the ecosystem is designed
          to run on your own infrastructure if you'd rather not use the hosted version.
        </p>
        <p><a href={githubOrgUrl}>Follow the project on GitHub</a></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
